(Wiedemann)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Stein" authorityName="Stein" authorityYear="1909" box="[1076,1328,439,464]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Pygophora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="454" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maculipennis">
<emphasis box="[1076,1257,439,464]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="454">P. maculipennis</emphasis>
Stein
</taxonomicName>
, but it is distinguished from them by having 1 posteroventral seta on hind tibia and slender surstylus in dorsal view in male. However, females of 
<taxonomicName box="[391,538,511,536]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Pygophora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="454" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="boninensis">
<emphasis box="[391,538,511,536]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="454">P. boninensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are not able to identify without locality data.
</paragraph>
